    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-15T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-15T22:00:00-05:00" n="131"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d131">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94119/406: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-16T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 16, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 16—10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>163. Department’s 87, February 28, 6 p.m. Doctor J. Leighton Stuart<note n="92"
                        xml:id="d131fn92">American, president of Yenching University, near
                        Peiping.</note> arrived in Hankow on March 11. I saw Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs<note n="93" xml:id="d131fn93">Wang Chung-hui.</note> afternoon March
                    12 and communicated to him Department’s message. Minister for Foreign Affairs
                    stated that he thoroughly understood and said that he would convey information
                    to members of Government who might be approached by Stuart. I saw Stuart on
                    March 15. He stated that he had had an interview with the Generalissimo but had
                    not communicated Wang Keh Min’s<note n="94" xml:id="d131fn94">Head of
                        Japanese-sponsored regime at Peiping.</note> message as he discovered very
                    quickly that there was no basis for any hope of mediation. Stuart said that his
                    visit to Hankow had convinced him that peace between China and Japan was not yet
                    possible.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping and Shanghai. Shanghai please repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
